						               													<description>How many scarves can you collect for your giraffe? Roll the dice, pick a card and build your giraffe in this fun counting and colour matching game. The winner is the player with the most scarves on their giraffe!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The exciting and engaging gameplay is sure to hold children's attention play after play, testing a number of different educational skills...from basic colour matching and counting to memory, strategy and turn taking. The quirky and beautifully illustrated giraffe characters are sure to provide lots of laughs too!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Designed for ages 4-7, Giraffes in Scarves offers the perfect balance between learning and fun! It can also be played by up to 6 players.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;On a player's turn roll the dice and choose a card with a matching colored spot. If the card is a neck card, add it to your giraffe&amp;rsquo;s neck.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;If you turn over your head card and there is no neck card on your giraffe, return it face down to the table and mix up the cards. If the head card matches your giraffe body and you have one more next cards, place the head at the top of your giraffe's neck. You can not add any more neck cards, but can continue to turn over cards on your turn.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;If you turn over another player's head card and you do not have a finished giraffe, return the card face down to the table and mix up the cards. If you turn over a head card which matches another player&amp;rsquo;s giraffe body and your giraffe is already finished, place the head at the top of their giraffe. This will end their chances of adding any more scarves.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Play continues until all player&amp;rsquo;s giraffes are finished. Each player count show many scarves their giraffe is wearing.The winner is the player with he most scarves at the end of the game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Contents:&amp;#10;24 neck cards&amp;#10;6 head cards&amp;#10;6 base boards&amp;#10;1 colour dice&amp;#10;1 instruction leaflet&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Not suitable for children under 3 years due to small parts. Choking hazard.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
